05283nam a22008295i 9780231546331DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017055402  a97802315463317 a10.7312/chia185782doi  a(DE-B1597)502707  a(OCoLC)1046678375  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHQ1075.5.C6bC45 2018 4aHQ1075.5.C6bC45 2018eb 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a305.309512231 aChiang, Howard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAfter Eunuchs :bScience, Medicine, and the Transformation of Sex in Modern China /cHoward Chiang. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource :b51 images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Toward a Genealogy of Sex -- tI. China Castrated -- tII. Vital Visions -- tIII. Deciphering Desire -- tIV. Mercurial Matter -- tV. Transsexual Taiwan -- tConclusion: China Trans Formed -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor much of Chinese history, the eunuch stood out as an exceptional figure at the margins of gender categories. Amid the disintegration of the Qing Empire, men and women in China began to understand their differences in the language of modern science. In After Eunuchs, Howard Chiang traces the genealogy of sexual knowledge from the demise of eunuchism to the emergence of transsexuality, showing the centrality of new epistemic structures to the formation of Chinese modernity.From anticastration discourses in the late Qing era to sex-reassignment surgeries in Taiwan in the 1950s and queer movements in the 1980s and 1990s, After Eunuchs explores the ways the introduction of Western biomedical sciences transformed normative meanings of gender, sexuality, and the body in China. Chiang investigates how competing definitions of sex circulated in science, medicine, vernacular culture, and the periodical press, bringing to light a rich and vibrant discourse of sex change in the first half of the twentieth century. He focuses on the stories of gender and sexual minorities as well as a large supporting cast of doctors, scientists, philosophers, educators, reformers, journalists, and tabloid writers, as they debated the questions of political sovereignty, national belonging, cultural authenticity, scientific modernity, human difference, and the power and authority of truths about sex. Theoretically sophisticated and far-reaching, After Eunuchs is an innovative contribution to the history and philosophy of science and queer and Sinophone studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aGender identityzChina. 0aGender identity. 0aSex rolezChina. 0aSocial perception. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishz978311060403008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018z9783110603149oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/chia1857840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231546331423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231546331/original  a978-3-11-060403-0  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11